04993nam a22007935i 9780271082639DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20202019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710826397 a10.1515/97802710826392doi  a(DE-B1597)583812  a(OCoLC)1253313686  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0090002bisacsh1 aCarrier, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAesthetics of the Margins / The Margins of Aesthetics :bWild Art Explained /cJoachim Pissarro, David Carrier. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b32 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Modern Foundations of the Art World -- t2 The Classical Model: Dogmatism and Alternative Models of Looking -- t3. Dawn of Modernity -- t4. The Wise, the Ignorant, and the Possibility of an Art World That Transcends This Divide -- t5. The Antinomy of Taste and Its Solution: Variations on a Theme by Duchamp -- t6. The Museum Era -- t7. Institutionalization of Art History -- t8. Art Beyond the Boundaries of the Art World -- t9. The Fluid Nature of Aesthetic Judgments -- t10. Kitsch, a Nonconcept: A Genealogy of the Indesignatable -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Wild Art” refers to work that exists outside the established, rarified world of art galleries and cultural channels. It encompasses uncatalogued, uncommodified art not often recognized as such, from graffiti to performance, self-adornment, and beyond. Picking up from their breakthrough book on the subject, Wild Art, David Carrier and Joachim Pissarro here delve into the ideas driving these forms of art, inquire how it came to be marginalized, and advocate for a definition of “taste,” one in which each expression is acknowledged as being different while deserving equal merit.Arguing that both the “art world” and “wild art” have the same capacity to produce aesthetic joy, Carrier and Pissarro contend that watching skateboarders perform Christ Air, for example, produces the same sublime experience in one audience that another enjoys while taking in a ballet; therefore, both mediums deserve careful reconsideration. In making their case, the two provide a history of the institutionalization of “taste” in Western thought, point to missed opportunities for its democratization in the past, and demonstrate how the recognition and acceptance of “wild art” in the present will radically transform our understanding of contemporary visual art in the future.Provocative and optimistic, Aesthetics of the Margins / The Margins of Aesthetics rejects the concept of “kitsch” and the high/low art binary, ultimately challenging the art world to become a larger and more inclusive place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aArt World.  aArt museum.  aCritique of the Art Establishment.  aFolk Art.  aGraffiti.  aHegel.  aHistory of Aesthetics.  aInstitutional Critique.  aKant.  aMuseum History.  aOutsider Art.  aPublic Art.  aWild art.1 aPissarro, Joachim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108263940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271082639423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271082639/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUA